    <ul  >
    <li>The month of September that includes the zodiac signs of Virgo and Libra has an assortment of 12 stones listed as birthstones.</li>
	<li>The birthstones marked for September are sapphire, agate, moonstone, zircon, peridot (chrysolite), and sardonyx.</li>
	<li>The zodiac signs add on six more birthstones: citrine, carnelian, jade, jasper, opal, and lapis lazuli.</li>
    </ul>
 
 <span class="birthstoneinfoheader">Sapphire- September Birthstone</span>
<p  >&quot;Sapphirus&quot; in Greek means blue, and this is how the sapphire got its popular name. It may also come from the Persian word 'safir' meaning beloved of the Saturn. Sapphire occupies a place of pride among gemstones both for its deep alluring hues and beauty. The symbolic meaning of the color blue has a Biblical meaning symbolizing heavenly grace.</p>
 
 <span class="birthstoneinfoheader">Physical and Chemical Properties</span>
<p  >Sapphire belongs to the family of mineral corundum. Corundum is found in all colors of the rainbow, the red being designated as ruby and all other hues as Sapphire. But the most loved and known color of Sapphire is a rich, deep blue. Other colors include yellow, orange, green, pink, purple etc. Sapphires are very hard mineral, actually second to only diamonds in hardness. They have a value of 9 on the Mohs scale. The way corundum crystal formation occurs, makes it unusual for very large crystals to form. Sapphires exhibit a special optical property called asterism which is responsible for the star shaped effect seen in star sapphires making them rare and valued.</p>
 
 <span class="birthstoneinfoheader">Geographical Information</span>
<p  >Sapphires are mined from alluvial deposits or from primary underground workings. Sapphires were mined as early as the 7th Century BC from India which is now Sri Lanka. They are found today in Sri Lanka, Kashmir, Myanmar, Thailand, Australia and some parts of Africa, China, Kenya, Tanzania and the United States.</p>
 
